description.plain:
Dominique Armani Jones (born December 3, 1994) better known by his stage name Lil Baby, has established himself as a global force from the Atlanta hip-hop scene. From growing up with fellow Atlanta rapper, Young Thug to many arrests and struggles with poverty, Baby has experienced tremendous growth since starting to rap in 2017.

Raised by his single mother, Baby was born into poverty with his two sisters and one brother. He lived off of food stamps and government assistance. In January 2012, he was arrested and charged with burglary. Later that year in August, he attempted to drop out of tenth grade but once again was arrested for possession of dangerous drugs. Two more marijuana possessions and one more theft charge put him in jail for two years. It was during his time in jail when Quality Control Music’s Pee and Coach K encouraged Baby to pursue a career in rapping.

He released his first mixtape on April 14, 2017, with Perfect Timing. The project features fellow Atlanta rappers, Lil Yachty, frequent collaborator Gunna, and childhood friend, Young Thug. Baby immediately rose to fame and attracted many listeners. This led him to drop two more mixtapes, Harder Than Hard and Too Hard, in the same year.

Baby’s debut studio album, Harder Than Ever peaked on the US Billboard 200 at the number 3 spot. The tape’s lead single, “Southside,” peaked at number 79 on the US Billboard Hot 100 while the second single, “Yes Indeed,” features Drake and topped off at number 6 on the charts.

Following the release of Drip Harder, a collaborative album with Gunna, Lil Baby released his fourth mixtape, Street Gossip. His February 2020 sophomore studio album, My Turn, went on to become the best selling album in the United States. The deluxe version of album features the viral hit “We Paid” with 42 Dugg.

songs.title: Freestyle

description.plain:
One of Atlanta, Georgia native Lil Baby’s breakout hits, “Freestyle” helped to introduce the rapper to audiences back in November 2017. The track’s lyrics address Baby’s rise to stardom as well as his usage of the recreational drug lean. In a May 2018 Breakfast Club interview, Lil Baby discussed his decision to eventually stop using lean:

That shit started fuckin' with me… like, breathe different, talk different, feel different, like, everything.

“Freestyle” was an early contributor towards Lil Baby’s successful career: the song’s music video, which was released on November 5, 2017, has accumulated over 300 million views. The track eventually appeared on Baby’s December 2017 mixtape Too Hard.

songs.title: Close Friends

description.plain:
On this song, Lil Baby discusses the importance of becoming “Close Friends” with a woman before dating her. However, their relationship has soured due to Baby’s unfaithful actions, and he’s now pleading to her to love him again.

Jayda Cheaves, Lil Baby’s girlfriend and the mother of his child, first previewed a portion of this song on Instagram Live on May 31, 2018. The song is likely about their relationship, as Baby publicly admitted to cheating on Cheaves in April 2018.

Alongside “Deep End,” this is the second of two solo songs by Baby on Drip Harder.

songs.title: On Me

description.plain:
Lil Baby reflects on how he deals with wealth and success on the long-awaited “On Me.” While the song finds Baby depicting his lavish lifestyle, the rapper also gets introspective, acknowledging his weaknesses and taking a wiser approach to his spending.

The song was first teased on October 7, 2020, by IJU Productions, the production company of the track’s accompanying music video. Multiple excerpts were further teased in late 2020 by Baby and his girlfriend, Jayda Cheaves.

songs.title: The Bigger Picture

description.plain:
“The Bigger Picture” is a protest song from Lil Baby, featuring the rapper commenting on police brutality and systemic racism in America in the wake of the murder of George Floyd.

The track comes just days after Baby went out and protested on the streets of Atlanta on June 8, 2020. At the protest, Baby was a leading force, leading the crowd on his bicycle (as depicted on the single’s cover art) as well as handing out protestors supplies and money and speaking in front of the crowd when they reached the march’s destination of Georgia’s State Capitol Building.

songs.title: Emotionally Scarred

description.plain:
“Emotionally Scarred” finds Lil Baby looking back at the influence that his old hood life left on his mindset. The rapper recalls being poor and explains that his come-up forced him to cut off many people from his entourage. A few days before the release of My Turn, Baby told The New York Times:

I don’t miss my old life at all. Period.

The three-minute song is one of the five tracks on My Turn produced by frequent collaborator Twysted Genius and  stands out as one of the breakout hits from the album.

songs.title: Woah

description.plain:
“Woah” is the second single from Lil Baby’s sophomore studio album, My Turn. On the track, he taunts his haters and raps about the luxuries of his lifestyle. The song is seemingly named after the “Woah,” (or “Hit the Woah”), a popular dance that originated in Texas in the mid-2010s and went viral on the Internet, most notably on TikTok.

After announcing the track on October 26, 2019, Baby teased a video snippet of it on November 1, in which he appears doing the “Woah” dance.

songs.title: Sum 2 Prove

description.plain:
“Sum 2 Prove” is Atlanta rapper Lil Baby’s third single for his sophomore studio album, My Turn. The track was officially announced by Baby’s record label Quality Control on January 5, 2020, on the label’s official Instagram account.

The song features Baby rapping in a braggadocios manner, flexing his wealth in terms of jewelry, cars, and the amount of monetary wealth he has.

Baby first teased a short snippet from this track on January 3, 2020, followed up by a longer snippet from the track three days later on January 6, 2020.

songs.title: Leaked

description.plain: “Leaked” is a song from Lil Baby’s May 2018 album Harder Than Ever. As the title implies, the song was prematurely leaked under the name “In My Bag” about a month before its official release. The main difference between the final version and the leaked version is that the leaked version has two more lines at the end of the first verse, then the song ends, with no repetition of the chorus and no second verse.

album.name: Harder Than Ever

body.plain: “Leaked” is a song from Lil Baby’s May 2018 album Harder Than Ever. As the title implies, the song was prematurely leaked under the name “In My Bag” about a month before its official release. The main difference between the final version and the leaked version is that the leaked version has two more lines at the end of the first verse, then the song ends, with no repetition of the chorus and no second verse.

songs.title: Ready

description.plain:
On “Ready”, Lil Baby teams up with longtime friend and frequent collaborator Gunna on a slow-tempo synth soundscape produced by Atlanta heavyweight Metro Boomin.

This track is the fifth track from Baby’s fourth mixtape, Street Gossip, which was released on November 30, 2018.

songs.full_title: Commercial by Lil Baby (Ft. Lil Uzi Vert)
songs.title: Commercial

description.plain:
“Commercial” marks Lil Baby’s and Lil Uzi Vert’s second collaboration. Baby originally announced that he would probably never release this song after he previewed his first verse in late 2019.

The song was however announced to be part of Baby’s sophomore album My Turn before being leaked in its entirety a few days before the release of the album. Uzi’s verse was most likely recorded in the month before the song’s release, given Lil Uzi’s allusion to Kobe Bryant’s passing away in January 2020.

description.plain:
“All of a Sudden” is the third track from Lil Baby’s Too Hard mixtape. It was re-released as a single on April 20th, 2018.

This marks the first collaboration between Lil Baby and Moneybagg Yo. The two discuss guns, drugs, women, jewelry, and their rapid success.

On “Time”, Lil Baby is seen teaming up with Meek Mill for the first time. On the track, the two reminsice about jail time, whilst also touching on their new expensive watches, which can tell the time.
Baby has been arrested for drug possession, while Meek has been arrested multiple times for various issues, including fights and probation violations.

songs.full_title: Never Needed No Help by Lil Baby
songs.title: Never Needed No Help

description.plain:
“Never Needed No Help” is a standout track from his project Harder Than Ever. This record is about how Lil Baby, who is signed to Quality Music Control, made it on his own after taking his rap career seriously in 2017.
This is a beautiful testament to his ability to create solo bangers although he boasts massive features from the likes of Drake, Lil Uzi Vert, Gunna, Young Thug, etc.

songs.full_title: Forever by Lil Baby (Ft. Lil Wayne)
songs.title: Forever

description.plain:
On “Forever,” Lil Baby and Lil Wayne discuss their refusal to sell out to the evils of the rap game and forever remain true to themselves. This marks the second official collaboration between the two.

A snippet of the song was first posted in May 2019, and Baby would also preview Wayne’s verse months later. In January 2020, the song leaked in its entirety before receiving an official release on My Turn. The final version has a number of minor differences in the instrumental and vocal effects.

songs.title: Global

description.plain:
In the first Track if Lil Baby’s album “Street Gossip”, Baby explains the hardships of becoming the well-known and accomplished rapper that he is today.

Going in depth on his hard work and dedication, Baby expresses himself by saying he “can’t stop, cause they depend on me”. Even before that he states the mental struggles that come with the hard path of becoming successful, “Sometimes I feel like the floor is giving in on me”.

songs.full_title: In A Minute by Lil Baby
songs.title: In A Minute

description.plain:
In “In A Minute,” Atlanta native Lil Baby raps about his extravagant lifestyle after coming from a treacherous background. Throughout the track, Baby also switches between topics from his wealth to firearms and ammunition.

The song was released as a surprise drop by Baby alongside his highly anticipated “Right On.” It was also released with its official music video which sees Baby performing at shows, flexing his jewellery, and shopping at expensive stores.

songs.title: Right On

description.plain:
“Right On” was first previewed by Anthony Edwards on November 22, 2021. After this one snippet the song became very popular all over TikTok. On December 8, a seller put up a Cdq snippet for the song randomly. The song eventually leaked in full quality on December 9, 2021.
Lil Baby would then drop the song officially with a music video on April 8, 2022.

songs.title: Social Distancing

description.plain:
“Social Distancing“ is a standout track off of the deluxe of My Turn. On the track, Lil Baby uses the current social distancing recommendation – due to the COVID-19 pandemic – as a metaphor to emphasize how far ahead of the competition he is. Dropping references to expensive items and rich girls, Baby boasts about his lifestyle with fame.

On April 14, Baby teased the track by tweeting a line from the track:

https://twitter.com/lilbaby4PF/status/1250086899659702278?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw

songs.title: Errbody

description.plain:
“Errbody” is a single released by Atlanta rapper Lil Baby. After his birthday, Baby blessed the fans with two surprise releases and this track is one of them. After a very successful 2020, he released this song with an official video alongside it.

https://twitter.com/lilbaby4PF/status/1334545466822959105

Throughout the song, Baby drops a number of names including athletes and other artists. He makes it clear in the hook that his fashion sense and appearance can’t be compared to anyone. He talks about his money and spendings in the single. He also said his biggest challenges outside of the music industry are to stay solid and not lose anything. Baby says:

Nowadays a lot of people depend on me. It’s a hard challenge for me, with all the distractions and shit. So that’s like the main thing to me, managing my money the right way.”

songs.title: Live Off My Closet

description.plain: In “Live Off My Closet”, Lil Baby and Future deliver some quick-paced flows over a mysterious xylophone arrangement with heavy bass from producer Twysted Genius. This dynamic duo rap about expensive clothing, drugs, cars, chains and women, while repeatedly boasting about the value of the merchandise they own in their closet, and expressing how it could sustain their lifestyle if they were to ever be in financial straits. The pair also likens themselves to Hugh Hefner and mention singer Rihanna during this high-powered banger.

songs.title: Get Ugly

description.plain:
With “Get Ugly,” Lil Baby introduces the listener to the ambitious mood of My Turn, his sophomore album.

The song is produced by fellow Atlanta native ATL Jacob and finds Lil Baby rapping about how far he’s come, as well as elaborating on his current lifestyle. The triumphant tone carried by the lyrics of “Get Ugly” is in line with that featured in Baby’s previous intro songs, such as 2018’s “Global” and “Intro (Harder Than Ever).”

songs.title: Right Now

description.plain:
On “Right Now,” Lil Baby recruits fellow Atlanta rapper for a very introspective song.

Over an instumental produced by Thug’s frequent collaborator London on da Track, the two rappers reflect on what the success they earned implies in their private lifes, including their relationships.

songs.title: Hurtin

description.plain: “Hurtin” is the 18th track on Lil Baby’s second studio album “My Turn”. In this song, Baby shows a more sensitive and emotional side of himself as shown in other tracks including “Close Friends” and “Emotionally Scarred”. It is produced by Quay Global who is a frequent collaborator with Lil Baby.

description.plain: “Real as it Gets” is a track by Lil Baby featuring EST Gee. It was teased on Lil Baby’s Instagram live twice before leaking on January 28, 2021, under the name “Never Lackin”. The song officially dropped on March 4, 2021, along with the music video. Produced by ATL Jacob & DY Krazy, it was believed that this song would be on Lil Baby’s upcoming mixtape “Lamborghini Boys.”

songs.full_title: Section 8 by Lil Baby (Ft. Young Thug)
songs.title: Section 8

description.plain:
Over a classic Wheezy produced beat, “Section 8” finds childhood friends Lil Baby and Young Thug celebrating their rise to wealth and fame out of the projects of Atlanta.

Baby and Thugger grew up in Section 8 housing in a very poor, violent part of Atlanta and went to school together. In an interview with GQ, one of Thug’s first managers detailed just how poor he was when he began: “He had nothing… Like a few shirts, a pair of shoes… He didn’t have the gold front teeth yet; his teeth were rotted, discolored. He covered them with his hand when he talked.”

Using lines like “We got them foreigns outside of the ‘partment, Look like a dealership” and “I'ma cop 20 Plain Janes, and I’m passin’ ‘em right around” the two Atlanta rappers juxtapose their humble beginnings with anecdotes of their now opulent lifestyles.

description.plain:
Lil Baby makes a surprise come back with ‘Frozen’, dropping the song 4 months after it leaked on December 25, 2021.

The manner in which it’s working out, it appears as though Lil Baby will have an inconceivable summer. Only a couple of evenings back, it was declared that he and Chris Brown were going out on visit and that declaration emerged after Ed Sheeran added Lil Baby to his ‘2Step’ record.

You could recollect that at the highest point of the month, the Atlanta rapper delivered two new melodies ‘In A Minute’ and ‘Right On’.

songs.full_title: Anyway by Lil Baby (Ft. 2 Chainz & Gucci Mane)
songs.title: Anyway

description.plain:
Lil Baby teams up with Gucci Mane and 2 Chainz for an all-Atlanta trap banger produced by frequent Baby producer, Quay Global.

The song sees them trading verses flexing their lavish lifestyles and seemingly effortless access to luxury as Baby touts in the hook he can “Pull up any kind of way I wanna.”

songs.title: For Me

description.plain:
Baby first teased this track on February 9, 2021 with a video posted on social media filmed by Caleb Jermale of IJU Productions, the cinematographer who also shot Baby’s previews of “On Me”, posted October 7, 2020, and “God’s My Witness,” posted earlier the same day.

The song’s title is currently unconfirmed and it is unclear if Baby will ever release this song.

songs.title: Seattle (Song 3)

description.plain: “Seattle” is a song by Lil Baby, both recorded and leaked in 2018. The file name that leaked with the song was “Song 3 Seattle RUFF.mp3,” and other songs recorded around the same time had similar file names with different song numbers. So this song is basically untitled, but it’s the third song Lil Baby made and named “Seattle.”

songs.full_title: Toast Up by Lil Baby (Ft. Ali Tomineek & ShadOnTheBeat)
songs.title: Toast Up

description.plain:
“Toast Up” is an independent single from Lil Baby. It is the result of the Doritos Spark the Beat Challenge, in which an artist, Ali Tomineek, and producer, Shad on the Beat, were selected to receive $100,000 and collaborate with Lil Baby in-studio.

The contest began on July 11, 2019, and lasted until September 8, 2019. Contestants were given a demo of Lil Baby’s verse and a sample to work with. They uploaded their version of the track to the Spark the Beat website to confirm their submissions. Entries were reviewed by a panel that included Lil Baby.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qmB2_uttip4
